ğ‡ğ¨ğ° ğˆâ€™ğ ğ©ğ«ğ¨ğœğğ¬ğ¬ ğš ğŸğŸ ğ“ğ ğŸğ¢ğ¥ğ ğ¢ğ§ ğ€ğ©ğšğœğ¡ğ ğ’ğ©ğšğ«ğ¤ ğƒğšğ¢ğ¥ğ² - ğ¬ğ­ğğ© ğ›ğ² ğ¬ğ­ğğ©:
20 TB daily isnâ€™t a casual batch job.
We need to finish it in a few hours - not days - and do it every single day.
So the first question isnâ€™t â€œwhat code,â€
itâ€™s â€œwhat cluster can handle this load reliably?â€
I'll go with below setup

Worker nodes = 50   
Cores per node = 16   
Memory per node = 128 GB  

ğŸ’¡ That gives:
 â€¢ 50 Ã— 16 = 800 cores
 â€¢ 50 Ã— 128 = 6.4 TB total memory
But we canâ€™t use all of that - Spark shares each node with the OS and Hadoop daemons.

Each node runs its own OS + NodeManager + Spark overhead.
So we leave 1 core + 8 GB RAM per node for system processes.
That leaves:
 â€¢ 15 cores and 120 GB usable memory per node
 â†’ 50 nodes Ã— 15 cores = 750 cores total
 â†’ 50 nodes Ã— 120 GB = 6 TB usable memory

Now the real Spark math starts.
We donâ€™t want one big executor per node - too much GC overhead.
Nor do we want 16 tiny ones - too much scheduling overhead.
Thumb Rule: 3â€“5 cores per executor â†’ sweet spot = 4.
So per node:
15 cores Ã· 4 â‰ˆ 3 executors (1 core idle is fine).
Memory = 120 GB Ã· 3 = 40 GB per executor â†’ after 10 % overhead â‰ˆ 36 GB usable.
Each executor â†’ 4 cores + 36 GB RAM.
Executors per node = 3 â†’ 150 executors total.
ğŸ§® Total cluster usage by Spark =
 â€¢ 150 Ã— 4 = 600 cores
 â€¢ 150 Ã— 36 = 5.4 TB RAM
The rest (~25 %) stays reserved for system + shuffle overhead â€” the safe zone.

Spark runs one task per core.
So 600 parallel tasks = 600 partitions processed at a time.
For 20 TB Parquet data (~512 MB per partition):
 â€¢ 20 TB / 0.5 GB â‰ˆ 40,000 partitions.
Waves = 40000 / 600 â‰ˆ 67 waves of tasks.
Each wave = a batch of 600 parallel tasks â†’ after 67 waves, job done 

Optimization Principles
1ï¸âƒ£ Use columnar compression (Parquet + Snappy).
2ï¸âƒ£ Partition by date or region for pruning.
3ï¸âƒ£ Tune spark.sql.shuffle.partitions = 600 to match cores.
4ï¸âƒ£ Broadcast small tables â†’ avoid heavy shuffles.
5ï¸âƒ£ Compact tiny files â†’ 512 MB target size.
6ï¸âƒ£ Checkpoint long DAGs â†’ no recomputation loops
______________________________________________________________
Databricks Jobs Are Slow â€” Usually for These 6â€“7 Core Reasons 

1ï¸âƒ£ Data Skew (Hot Keys)
Symptom: A few tasks take hours while others finish in seconds.
Cause: Uneven data distribution â€” one key has too much data.
Fix: Add salting to hot keys, use repartition, or broadcast join when possible.
Check: Spark UI â†’ Stages â†’ task duration variance.

2ï¸âƒ£ Memory Spill to Disk
Symptom: Stages show heavy disk I/O during shuffle.
Cause: Executor memory insufficient for shuffle/join operations.
Fix:
1. Increase spark.executor.memory
2. Reduce cores per executor
3. Enable Photon (reduces memory pressure)
4. Monitor spill metrics in Spark UI â†’ Stages.

3ï¸âƒ£ Wrong Cluster Sizing
Symptom: Too slow or too costly.
Cause: Under-provisioned or over-provisioned clusters.
Fix:
1. Check CPU utilization in Spark UI â†’ Executors.
2. Scale up if CPU ~100%, scale down if mostly idle.
3. Use Autoscaling for variable workloads.

4ï¸âƒ£ Inefficient Joins & Shuffles
Symptom: Long shuffle time and large shuffle read/write sizes.
Cause: Sort-merge joins or unnecessary shuffles.
Fix:
1. Use broadcast joins for <1GB lookup tables.
2. Enable AQE (spark.sql.adaptive.enabled=true) for dynamic join optimization.
3. Repartition intelligently before joins.

5ï¸âƒ£ Cold Cache & Slow I/O
Symptom: First run slow, second run much faster.
Cause: Data read directly from cloud storage (S3/ADLS).
Fix:
1. Use Delta Lake with Liquid Clustering.
2. Run OPTIMIZE for compacted, co-located data.
3. Photon improves read speed 3â€“5x for Parquet/Delta.

6ï¸âƒ£ Small Files Problem (a.k.a. Too Many Tiny Files)
Symptom: Jobs spend time opening thousands of small files.
Cause: Frequent writes/appends create small files.
Fix:
1. Use OPTIMIZE in Delta to compact files.
2. Use mergeSchema and autoOptimize options.
3. Combine input data at source or before writing to Delta.

7ï¸âƒ£ Improper Partitioning or Missing Z-Ordering
Symptom: Full table scans despite filters.
Cause: Poor partition design or unclustered data.
Fix:
1. Partition on high-selectivity columns.
2. Use Liquid Clustering or Z-ORDER for frequently filtered columns.
3. Avoid over-partitioning (too many small partitions).

______________________________________________________________
1ï¸âƒ£ What happens when you run a Spark job?
Spark creates a DAG, breaks it into stages, converts them into tasks, and sends those tasks to executors for execution.
The driver coordinates the whole process.

2ï¸âƒ£ Driver vs Executors â€” whatâ€™s the difference?
	â€¢	Driver: creates the DAG, schedules stages, tracks metadata.
	â€¢	Executors: actually run the tasks and store data in memory/disk.

3ï¸âƒ£ What is a DAG?
A Directed Acyclic Graph of transformations.
It shows how your data flows from one step to the next, without cycles.
Spark uses it to optimize your job before execution.


4ï¸âƒ£ What are Narrow vs Wide transformations?
	â€¢	Narrow: each partition depends on a single parent partition (e.g., map, filter). â†’ No shuffle
	â€¢	Wide: data must move across partitions (e.g., groupBy, join). â†’ Shuffle happens

This one is critical â€” most performance issues come from wide transformations.


5ï¸âƒ£ What is a Stage?
A group of tasks that can run without a shuffle.
A shuffle boundary creates a new stage.


6ï¸âƒ£ What triggers a Shuffle?
Wide transformations like:
groupBy, agg, join, distinct, repartition, orderBy.
If Spark needs to move data across nodes â†’ shuffle.

7ï¸âƒ£ What is a Task in Spark?
The smallest unit of work, run on executors.
Each task processes one partition of data.


8ï¸âƒ£ How does Spark achieve fault tolerance?
Through lineage.
Instead of storing intermediate results, Spark knows how data was created and can recompute lost partitions if an executor fails.

9ï¸âƒ£ What does a Cluster Manager do?
YARN / Kubernetes / Standalone:
It allocates resources (CPU, memory) to Spark applications
but does not schedule tasks â€” the driver does that.

ğŸ”Ÿ What changes when AQE (Adaptive Query Execution) is enabled?
Spark can:
	â€¢	Detect skew at runtime
	â€¢	Change join strategy on the fly
	â€¢	Merge/split shuffle partitions
Basically, Spark becomes smarter during execution, not just before it.
