Batch processing deals with large data sets in bulk â€” itâ€™s great for analytics and reporting where latency isnâ€™t critical. Real-time processing, 
on the other hand, processes data continuously as it arrives â€” useful when immediate insights or actions are required.
For example, a bank might use real-time processing to detect fraudulent transactions instantly, but use batch processing to generate end-of-day reports.
The trade-off is between latency and complexity â€” batch is simpler and cheaper, while real-time gives instant insights but requires more complex infrastructure.

